Every Java program lives inside a class.
The entry point is always the main method:

public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, world! 🌸");
    }
}

To compile and run:
  javac HelloWorld.java    <- compiles to HelloWorld.class
  java HelloWorld          <- runs it

Key things to notice:
  • Class name MUST match the filename
  • main method signature is always the same
  • Statements end with semicolons
  • Curly braces define blocks

Primitive types (lowercase):
  int      integer          int x = 42;
  long     big integer      long n = 123456789L;
  double   decimal          double pi = 3.14;
  float    small decimal    float f = 3.14f;
  boolean  true/false       boolean ok = true;
  char     single char      char c = 'A';
  byte     -128 to 127      byte b = 100;
  short    small integer    short s = 1000;

Object types (capitalized):
  String   text             String s = "hello";
  Integer  int wrapper      Integer x = 42;
  Double   double wrapper
  Boolean  boolean wrapper

Arrays:
  int[] nums = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
  String[] names = new String[10];
  nums[0]   <- access first element

Java is object-oriented. Everything is a class.

Defining a class:
public class Dog {
    // fields (attributes)
    String name;
    int age;

    // constructor
    public Dog(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age  = age;
    }

    // method
    public void bark() {
        System.out.println(name + " says: Woof!");
    }
}

Using the class:
Dog myDog = new Dog("Luna", 3);
myDog.bark();   // Luna says: Woof!
System.out.println(myDog.name);   // Luna

Inheritance — a class can extend another:
public class Animal {
    String name;
    public void speak() { System.out.println("..."); }
}

public class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    public void speak() {
        System.out.println(name + " says: Meow!");
    }
}

Interfaces — define a contract:
public interface Drawable {
    void draw();   // must be implemented
}

public class Circle implements Drawable {
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a circle");
    }
}

Key OOP concepts:
  Encapsulation  hide data with private + getters/setters
  Inheritance    extend classes with extends
  Polymorphism   same method, different behaviour
  Abstraction    abstract classes and interfaces

Java's Collections Framework:

ArrayList — dynamic array:
  ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
  list.add("apple");
  list.add("banana");
  list.get(0);          // apple
  list.size();          // 2
  list.remove(0);

HashMap — key-value pairs:
  HashMap<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
  map.put("alice", 90);
  map.put("bob",   85);
  map.get("alice");     // 90
  map.containsKey("bob");   // true

HashSet — unique values:
  HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();
  set.add("a");
  set.add("a");   // ignored, already in set
  set.size();     // 1

Iterate with for-each:
  for (String item : list) {
      System.out.println(item);
  }

Exceptions handle errors gracefully:

try {
    int result = 10 / 0;   // ArithmeticException!
    System.out.println(result);
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero");
} finally {
    System.out.println("This always runs");
}

Common exceptions:
  NullPointerException      used null reference
  ArrayIndexOutOfBounds     bad array index
  NumberFormatException     bad string-to-number
  IOException               file/network error
  ClassCastException        invalid type cast

Throwing your own:
  public void setAge(int age) {
      if (age < 0)
          throw new IllegalArgumentException("Age cannot be negative");
      this.age = age;
  }

Custom exception:
  public class PinkException extends Exception {
      public PinkException(String msg) { super(msg); }
  }
